Pets are a wash IMO.  So many classes have pets and by the time these classes reach lvl 60 they can use there pets more effectively then a mage.  Yes a shaman pet isnt as powerful as mage pet, but a Shaman is a more powerful spell caster then a mage. The Shaman's pets aids him in all the correct ways when it comes to killing a mob. This is the same for necros.  Mage pets are really not as useful to the mage as they are to the other three primary pet classes. Instead of our spell casting power being great and pets enhancing that power it is the total opposite.  Pets are most all of a magicians power and our spells casting power overall is low.  No other class in the game is so dependant on a summoned NPC to protect them or be there main tool of offensive attack. I truly believe that because mage pets have been disigned to be both is where the flaw lies.  Verant needs to decide one of two things.  Either mage pets are defensive or offensive. We cant have so much tied into a summoned NPC that doesnt zone with us, doesnt remain after we go LD, cant do much if there is more then one mob and isnt used on most raids.  Pets in all forms have to many design flaws to force any class to be totally dependant on them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rhasinfirestorm>Rhasin Firestorm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 385<br> <font color=#333333>(2/27/02 1:50:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: umm then what is the</span><hr size=1> Wezloc,<br>
<br>
I think part of your communication issue (this is what I have come to understand is the problem with why I tend to find your posts outrageous) is that you are using terms like 'Trivialize' improperly, at least to me.<br>
<br>
Trivialize = bad and unintended overpowering of an encounter with little to no risk involved (not as much risk as should be)<br>
<br>
Balance (or whatever it is) = An appropriate mix of power, ability and skill that makes harder encounters doable with risk still involved.<br>
<br>
A shaman slowing for 75% or a cleric complete healing <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> does not mean</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the encounter is trivial. It means harder encoutners are doable. The only encoutners it trivializes (in accordance with the mob strength) is fighting high greens/light blues with a fair certanty you will win, no risk. VI intended slows and complete heals to be used, so they iincreased mob damage output (hits 150+, doubles, possibly hasted). Complete heals and slows don't trivialize the encounter, the encounter is balanced intending for these things to be used. Without these skills and others, a full group would have to be healer heavy to keep up with the damage output from the mob, and then couldn't damage it enough because they couldn't muster the damage output fast enough before the mob (unslowed) beats the tank into the earth.<br>
<br>
People still die when a shaman slows (usually the shaman). People still die with a cleric complete healing. Risk is still present, the encounter is not 'trivial', just easier. <p><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=52886">Rhasin Firestorm</A><BR>
